<div class="header">
  <div class="header-content">
    <div class="tag">Compiled by Gemini 3.1</div>
    <h1>CSX Corporation (CSX)<br/>Intrinsic Value</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">A transparent, two-stage discounted cash flow valuation of CSX Corporation. — using FY2024 actuals, disclosed assumptions, and one final number.</p>
    <p class="date">Updated March 18, 2024 · Data: FY2024 10-K</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="container">
  <!-- ═══ THE VERDICT ═══ -->
  <div class="verdict-card">
    <div class="verdict-label">Estimated Intrinsic Value Per Share</div>
    <div class="verdict-price">{roundedIV !== null ? `$${roundedIV.toFixed(2)}` : "N/A"}</div>
    <div class="verdict-vs">vs. market price of {currentPrice !== null ? `$${currentPrice.toFixed(2)}` : "N/A"} ({marginOfSafety !== null ? marginOfSafety : "N/A"}%)</div>
    <div class="verdict-badge" style={`background: ${verdictColor}22; color: ${verdictColor}; border: 1px solid ${verdictColor}44;`}>
      {verdictText}
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ KEY METRICS ═══ -->
  <div class="stats-row">
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">$14.5B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">FY2024 Revenue</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">{fcfBase !== null ? `$${(fcfBase / 1000).toFixed(1)}B` : "N/A"}</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Free Cash Flow</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">$1.79</div>
      <div class="stat-label">EPS (Diluted)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">37.2%</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Operating Margin</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">{netCash !== null ? `-$${(Math.abs(netCash) / 1000).toFixed(1)}B` : "N/A"}</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Net Cash</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ METHODOLOGY ═══ -->
  <h2>Methodology: Two-Stage DCF</h2>
  <p>We use a <strong>two-stage discounted cash flow (DCF)</strong> model — the gold standard of intrinsic valuation. No multiples, no comparables, no vibes. Just future cash flows discounted to today.</p>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">1</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Start with actual Free Cash Flow</h4>
      <p>CSX generated <strong>$2.718 billion</strong> in free cash flow in FY2024. This is operating cash flow ($5.25B) minus capital expenditures ($2.53B). This represents the cash available to shareholders after all capital investments required to maintain the rail network.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">2</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Project FCF growth for 5 years (Phase 1)</h4>
      <p>We grow FCF at <strong>5% per year</strong> for 5 years. CSX is a mature Class I railroad with a durable economic moat and strong pricing power. While volumes have been relatively flat over recent years, consistent operational improvements and price escalations support modest, stable cash flow growth.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">3</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Calculate terminal value (Phase 2)</h4>
      <p>After Year 5, we assume FCF grows at <strong>2.5% forever</strong>. We use the <strong>Gordon Growth Model</strong>: Terminal Value = FCF₆ ÷ (discount rate − terminal growth rate). This roughly aligns with long-term macroeconomic GDP growth, acknowledging the integral nature of rail transport to the North American economy.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">4</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Discount everything to present value</h4>
      <p>All future cash flows are discounted at <strong>8.5%</strong>. This required rate of return reflects CSX's relatively stable earnings profile and monopolistic regional advantages, balanced against capital intensity and economic sensitivity.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">5</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Add net cash, divide by shares</h4>
      <p>Enterprise Value + Net Cash (-$18.06B) = Equity Value. Subtracting the significant debt load is critical for capital-intensive businesses like railroads. Divide by shares outstanding (1.94B) for the per-share intrinsic value.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ THE THREE ASSUMPTIONS ═══ -->
  <h2>The Three Assumptions That Drive Everything</h2>
  <p>A DCF is only as good as its inputs. We're making exactly <strong>three</strong> judgment calls — everything else is math. Here's what we chose and why.</p>

  <div class="assumption-grid">
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">FCF Growth Rate (Years 1-5)</div>
      <div class="value">5.0%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        Railroads generally grow at or slightly above nominal GDP due to their inflation-protected pricing power. Despite cyclical volume headwinds in some freight segments, CSX's ability to maintain high margins and control costs justifies a 5% medium-term growth assumption.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Discount Rate (WACC)</div>
      <div class="value">8.5%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        10Y Treasury: 4.18%. Given CSX's predictable duopoly status in the Eastern U.S., its cost of capital is somewhat lower than high-flying tech stocks, but the capital-intensive nature and heavy debt load warrant an 8.5% hurdle rate.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Terminal Growth Rate</div>
      <div class="value">2.5%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        Railroads have existed for over a century and represent the most fuel-efficient method of land transport. We assign a 2.5% perpetual growth rate, approximating long-term U.S. inflation and GDP growth, ensuring the model reflects a mature, enduring enterprise.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

