  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>No model is complete. Here's what a DCF inherently misses — and how it might bias our estimate.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Pricing power:</strong> If CSX can consistently raise rates above inflation without losing significant volume to trucking, margins could expand further.</li>
    <li><strong>Share repurchases:</strong> CSX has a strong history of returning capital via buybacks. Consistently shrinking the share count increases the intrinsic value per remaining share.</li>
    <li><strong>Operational efficiency:</strong> Further implementations of precision scheduled railroading (PSR) or new automation technologies could yield unexpected cost savings.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Economic sensitivity:</strong> Rail volumes are heavily tied to industrial production and consumer spending. A prolonged economic downturn would materially impact near-term cash flows.</li>
    <li><strong>Debt burden:</strong> With roughly $19 billion in debt, higher interest rates could increase debt servicing costs, eating into free cash flow and lowering equity value.</li>
    <li><strong>Regulatory environment:</strong> The Surface Transportation Board (STB) heavily regulates railroads. Changes in policies regarding reciprocal switching or rate caps could erode pricing power.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why is the Net Cash negative?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Railroads are extremely capital-intensive businesses and routinely carry large debt loads to finance their infrastructure. CSX has approximately $19 billion in total debt against just under $1 billion in cash. This is normal for the industry but requires deducting the net debt from the Enterprise Value to find the true Equity Value.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why use an 8.5% discount rate?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">An 8.5% rate reflects a solid risk premium over the 10-year Treasury yield (4.18%), accounting for the economic cyclicality of the transport sector while rewarding the oligopolistic, wide-moat nature of a Class I railroad.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why the significant drop in margins since 2021?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">2021 saw peak pricing power due to pandemic-related supply chain disruptions. Since then, inflation in materials, fuel, and particularly new labor agreements have increased operating ratios across the rail industry, compressing margins back to historical norms.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. Whether to buy depends on your personal risk tolerance, portfolio allocation, time horizon, tax situation, and conviction in the assumptions. We provide the tools and transparency — you make the decision.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

